\title{Quantifying Semantic Deviation in the Evolution of the English Language: A CPAF Approach}
\begin{document}
\maketitle

In this case study, we apply the Cognitive Progression Analysis Framework (CPAF) to explore the evolution of the English language over distinct time intervals—10, 50, and 100 years. 
Language, as a fundamental cognitive system, exhibits dynamic changes that reflect cultural, social, and technological shifts. 

By modeling whole words as entities and considering both letters (information value \(i_1\)) and meanings (weighted by the number of canonical definitions) as critical components, 
we aim to quantify semantic deviation (\(d\)) from a given baseline year. This analysis focuses on key linguistic processes: 
the archaism of words, changes in word meanings (e.g., "gay"), and the introduction of slang, viewing each as interactions that contribute to the overall deviation in the system. 
Slang, in particular, is conceptualized as a distinct deviation towards \(d=1\), representing a spectrum that culminates in the total replacement of a language. 
Through this lens, we seek to quantify semantic deviation values, offering insights into the adaptive and evolving nature of the English language as mediated by cognitive processes.

